import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the dataset
df = pd.read_csv('ecommerce_sales_data.csv')

# Clean column names (remove extra spaces)
df.columns = df.columns.str.strip()

# Print out the cleaned column names to ensure everything is correct
print("Cleaned Column Names:", df.columns)

# Ensure 'Purchase Date' column exists and check for any missing or incorrect date values
if 'Purchase Date' in df.columns:
    df['Purchase Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Purchase Date'], errors='coerce')

    # Check for any missing 'Purchase Date' values
    print(f"Missing 'Purchase Date' entries: {df['Purchase Date'].isnull().sum()}")

    # Drop rows with missing 'Purchase Date'
    df = df.dropna(subset=['Purchase Date'])

    # Set 'Purchase Date' as the index for time series analysis
    df.set_index('Purchase Date', inplace=True)

    # Resample the data to daily sales data (sum the 'Total Sales' column)
    df_daily = df.resample('D').agg({'Total Sales': 'sum'})

    # Fill missing values if needed (e.g., forward fill)
    df_daily.fillna(method='ffill', inplace=True)

    # Visualize the sales trend
    df_daily['Total Sales'].plot(figsize=(12, 6), title="Daily Sales Trend")
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Total Sales')
    plt.show()

else:
    print("Column 'Purchase Date' not found in the dataset.")

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the dataset
df = pd.read_csv('ecommerce_sales_data.csv')

# Clean column names (remove extra spaces)
df.columns = df.columns.str.strip()

# Ensure 'Purchase Date' is in datetime format
df['Purchase Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Purchase Date'], errors='coerce')

# Drop rows with missing 'Purchase Date'
df = df.dropna(subset=['Purchase Date'])

# Set 'Purchase Date' as the index for time series analysis
df.set_index('Purchase Date', inplace=True)

# Resample the data to daily sales data (sum the 'Total Sales' column)
df_daily = df.resample('D').agg({'Total Sales': 'sum'})

# Check for any missing dates after resampling
missing_dates = df_daily[df_daily['Total Sales'].isnull()]
print(f"Missing Dates (Total Sales = NaN):\n{missing_dates}")

# Fill missing values (use forward fill or backward fill, or leave as NaN)
# For forward-fill, uncomment the next line:
df_daily.fillna(method='ffill', inplace=True)  # Forward fill
# Alternatively, for backward fill, use the following:
# df_daily.fillna(method='bfill', inplace=True)  # Backward fill

# Visualize the daily sales trend after filling missing data
df_daily['Total Sales'].plot(figsize=(12, 6), title="Daily Sales Trend with Missing Data Handled")
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Total Sales')
plt.show()

# Save the aggregated and filled data to a CSV file for further analysis
df_daily.to_csv('aggregated_daily_sales_with_missing_data_handled.csv')

# Check for any remaining missing values after filling
print(f"Remaining missing values after filling: {df_daily.isnull().sum()}")

reakdown of the Code: Datetime Conversion: The 'Purchase Date' column is converted to datetime to ensure correct handling of time series data.

Resampling: The data is resampled to a daily frequency, summing the 'Total Sales' for each day.

Identifying Missing Dates: After resampling, we identify missing sales data for any day where 'Total Sales' is NaN.

Imputation:

Forward Fill: We use fillna(method='ffill') to fill missing sales data by carrying forward the last known value (useful for continuous data like sales).

Backward Fill: Alternatively, we can use fillna(method='bfill') to fill missing values using the next known value.

Visualization: The daily sales trend is plotted to visualize how sales are distributed over time after handling the missing data.

Saving: The cleaned and resampled data is saved to a CSV file for future analysis.

Handling Missing Dates: Missing Dates in Time Series: If any date in the series is missing (e.g., no sales on a particular day), resample will create a gap.

Filling Missing Data: Forward fill (ffill) is used to fill those gaps with the last known sales value, ensuring continuity in the data. Alternatively, you can leave them as gaps (NaN) or back-fill.

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose

# Load the cleaned and resampled data (daily sales data)
df_daily = pd.read_csv('aggregated_daily_sales_with_missing_data_handled.csv', index_col='Purchase Date', parse_dates=True)

# Check for trend by plotting the sales data
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(df_daily['Total Sales'], label='Daily Sales')
plt.title("Daily Sales Trend")
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Total Sales')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Trend Analysis: Use Rolling Mean to observe long-term trends
df_daily['Rolling Mean'] = df_daily['Total Sales'].rolling(window=30).mean()  # 30-day rolling mean
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(df_daily['Total Sales'], label='Daily Sales', alpha=0.5)
plt.plot(df_daily['Rolling Mean'], label='30-Day Rolling Mean', color='red', linewidth=2)
plt.title("Sales Trend with 30-Day Rolling Mean")
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Total Sales')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Seasonal Decomposition to check for seasonality
result = seasonal_decompose(df_daily['Total Sales'], model='multiplicative', period=365)  # Assume yearly seasonality

# Plot the decomposed components
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

plt.subplot(411)
plt.plot(result.observed, label='Observed')
plt.title('Observed')

plt.subplot(412)
plt.plot(result.trend, label='Trend', color='orange')
plt.title('Trend')

plt.subplot(413)
plt.plot(result.seasonal, label='Seasonal', color='green')
plt.title('Seasonal')

plt.subplot(414)
plt.plot(result.resid, label='Residual', color='red')
plt.title('Residual')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Check for seasonal spikes (e.g., festive periods like Diwali, New Year)
# For example, check if there are significant increases in sales during specific months (e.g., October or December for festive seasons)
df_daily['Month'] = df_daily.index.month
monthly_sales = df_daily.groupby('Month')['Total Sales'].sum()

# Plot Monthly Sales to detect seasonal patterns
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
monthly_sales.plot(kind='bar')
plt.title("Total Monthly Sales")
plt.xlabel('Month')
plt.ylabel('Total Sales')
plt.xticks(rotation=0)
plt.show()

# Anomaly detection: Detecting sudden spikes in sales (you can adjust the threshold)
threshold = df_daily['Total Sales'].quantile(0.95)  # 95th percentile as an anomaly threshold
anomalies = df_daily[df_daily['Total Sales'] > threshold]

# Plot anomalies
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(df_daily['Total Sales'], label='Daily Sales')
plt.scatter(anomalies.index, anomalies['Total Sales'], color='red', label='Anomalies', zorder=5)
plt.title("Sales with Anomalies")
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Total Sales')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Print anomalies for further investigation
print(f"Detected anomalies:\n{anomalies[['Total Sales']]}")

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose

# Load the cleaned data (ensure Purchase Date is the datetime index)
df_daily = pd.read_csv('aggregated_daily_sales_with_missing_data_handled.csv', index_col='Purchase Date', parse_dates=True)

# Resample data by month (summing total sales for each month)
df_monthly = df_daily.resample('M').sum()

# Ensure that there are enough data points for seasonal decomposition
# If you don't have 12 months of data, seasonal_decompose won't work as expected

# Check the length of the resampled data
print(f"Number of months of data: {len(df_monthly)}")

# Apply seasonal decomposition only if there are enough months (e.g., 12 months)
if len(df_monthly) >= 12:
    # Apply seasonal decomposition (with a period of 12 for monthly data)
    result = seasonal_decompose(df_monthly['Total Sales'], model='multiplicative', period=12)  # 12 months for yearly seasonality
    
    # Plot the decomposed components
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    
    plt.subplot(411)
    plt.plot(result.observed, label='Observed')
    plt.title('Observed')

    plt.subplot(412)
    plt.plot(result.trend, label='Trend', color='orange')
    plt.title('Trend')

    plt.subplot(413)
    plt.plot(result.seasonal, label='Seasonal', color='green')
    plt.title('Seasonal')

    plt.subplot(414)
    plt.plot(result.resid, label='Residual', color='red')
    plt.title('Residual')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    # Check for seasonal spikes (e.g., festive periods like Diwali, New Year)
    df_monthly['Month'] = df_monthly.index.month
    monthly_sales = df_monthly['Total Sales']

    # Plot Monthly Sales to detect seasonal patterns
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    monthly_sales.plot(kind='bar')
    plt.title("Total Monthly Sales")
    plt.xlabel('Month')
    plt.ylabel('Total Sales')
    plt.xticks(rotation=0)
    plt.show()
else:
    print("Not enough data to apply seasonal decomposition (need at least 12 months of data).")

from statsmodels.tsa.holtwinters import ExponentialSmoothing

# Apply Simple Exponential Smoothing (SES) without trend/seasonality
model = ExponentialSmoothing(df_monthly['Total Sales'], trend=None, seasonal=None)
model_fit = model.fit()

# Forecast next 6 months
forecast = model_fit.forecast(6)

# Plot the results
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(df_monthly.index, df_monthly['Total Sales'], label='Observed Sales')
plt.plot(df_monthly.index[-1] + pd.to_timedelta(range(1, 7), 'M'), forecast, label='Forecasted Sales', linestyle='--')
plt.title("Sales Forecast using Simple Exponential Smoothing (SES)")
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Sales')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
